			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Very well written and sums up many of my feelings on the current state of affairs for EQ.
<br />

<br />
In my eyes, GoD is the beginning of the end, even for the more hardcore players.  I've thought about it for a while now and I can sum up the major problems of this expansion in a few points:
<br />

<br />
1. Lengthy, comma-inducing time sinks.
<br />

<br />
I thought I'd seen the worst of tedious, boring time sinks in my time, but nothing could have prepared me for helping my guildmates finish up the Vxed and Tipt trials.
<br />
First off, we'll gloss over the entire lack of plot and storyline in GoD and just say it's enough that you can't get to Kod'Taz until you finish these trials.
<br />
With that in mind, you have 2 'expeditions' which take 3-4 hours to complete.  3-4 hours of nothing but killing hard-hitting mobs over and over and over, hoping you don't wipe due to a horribly inconvenient LD, mispull or lucky round of combat by a mob.
<br />

<br />
In addition, due to the difficulty of the mobs you fight and the fact they summon, certain classes such as warrior/paladin/enchanter/cleric will basically need to do these trials multiple times in order to get the entire guild flagged.
<br />

<br />
I would *love* to know which dev(s) at SoE thought it would be a great idea to require players to sit through a 3+ hour uninspired, boring event in order to even scratch the surface of GoD content.  I seriously don't know how anyone with a family could even think about taking part in this expansion with the sheer amount of time it takes to do these trials, coupled with lengthy CR's.  I thought the Vex Thall key quest was bad, but at least that forced you to explore Luclin, and generally most key pieces could be looted from players XPing in the zones or even killing mobs for an hour or two (don't get me wrong, I'm not a huge fan of that quest either).
<br />

<br />
2. Uninspired, boring zone/dungeon design.
<br />

<br />
One thing that really stands out about the original content of EQ (ie.. pre kunark) is the variety you had in that world.  You had everything from the deserts of North and South Ro to the icy hills of Everfrost Peaks.  The design of dungeons like SolB and LGuk were just downright awesome, in part due to the layout but also from the detail such as cobwebs, wall art, etc that gave a realistic and personal touch to the place.
<br />

<br />
Kunark took some getting used to. At first I got kinda sick of the 'ruined cities' theme that you saw in most zones, but I had a real appreciation for zones such as Sebilis, City of Mist and Kaesora.
<br />

<br />
The Velious expansion came across as a true labor of love.  Some of the best dungeon designs I'd ever seen; Crystal Caverns still stands out in my mind as one of the coolest and most visually appealing dungeons to date in EQ.
<br />

<br />
I'm not sure what happened past this point, but fast forward to GoD and you have some of the most generic, uninspired and tired looking zone design I've ever seen.  It just looks as if someone popped a few numbers into a zone generator and cranked out the zones.  Toss in some very odd and out-of-place looking mobs (I admit it's a matter of personal taste) that look like they escaped from one of the Quake games and you end up with a continent/expansion that I just don't care if I spend time in.
<br />

<br />
(continued.....)</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
