			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">3. Storyline does nothing to pull players in.
<br />

<br />
My impression was that GoD was supposed to usher in some new, horrible danger to Norath.  Invaders attacking us from another dimension has potential to be a truly world-altering event, but what could be a huge bang ends up as a tiny fizzle.  Not only is the entire expansion designed in such a way that locks out all but the most hardcore player, but the impact on Norath is nill.
<br />
You could argue that the timeline is such that the Muramites *just* came to Norath and haven't really invaded anything outside Taelosia, but why not have them showing up in other zones around Norath stirring up trouble?  How about a force of them invading Qeynos and changing the entire city and zones around it into a battleground.
<br />
If SoE wanted this expansion to be one that made us care about the future of Norath, they failed miserably.  At this point, the entire continent of Taelosia could sink into the sea and I don't think anyone would give 2 shits.
<br />

<br />
4. Content caters only to the players with practically unlimited playtime.
<br />

<br />
This kinda ties in with number 1, but progression in GoD is designed in such a way that if it isn't changed, I don't see the casual gamer ever being able to do much.  Again, much of the content is designed such that unless you can dedicate huge blocks of time to raiding and doing expeditions, you won't really be getting anywhere.  Furthermore, lack of any alternate means of progression means everyone has to work their way through the same bottlenecks.
<br />

<br />
For some reason, SoE has become obsessed with controlling the progression of players with no care for whether or not their game is actually fun or not.  I just know that lately when I log in, I find there simply isn't much to do and unless I have the next 3 or 4 hours free, there’s no point in getting involved in any GoD content.  I wish they devs could have taken a look at Velious.  It's a great example of an expansion that provided plenty of content for both high end guilds and casual players.
<br />

<br />
5. Faction and plot - give players a reason to care about the world they inhabit.
<br />

<br />
Faction is a great way to give players a chance to roleplay a bit and also presents people with choices.  For example, the Chardok quests were a great idea where players could ally themselves with the Sarnak, turn a dungeon into a city where they could run around unmolested, shop, bank, etc and also quest for nice items.  I think SoE could have taken this a step further by providing compelling alternatives and incentives to side with the Goblins of Droga.  Attaining higher levels of faction and possibly even giving players a title (Fred the Goblinbane/Sarnakslayer) are great alternatives to just flat out killing shit for no good reason.
<br />
In addition, players could choose to attack cities such as Freeport which might trigger scripts involving the town guards.  Players could collect heads from the guards and raise certain factions which might give them access to additional faction based quests in their home cities.  Players with exceptionally high factions might receive little perks in their home town such as their name on a wall plaque or something.
<br />
The basic concept here is that players should care about the gaming world they inhabit.  I can't think of any expansion or area I cared less about than Taelosia.
<br />

<br />
In conclusion, I have to also agree with what the previous poster mentioned regarding the Lore of EQ. There were many good storylines just within Original EQ, Kunark and Velious and I can't understand why they tossed it all out the window and went down the path they are now.
<br />

<br />
The world of EQ at this point is enormous in proportion, but much of it is totally empty.  Granted, players will generally flock to newer content but when an expansion is released and new effects placed on items, it stands to reason that at some point you need to go back and apply content updates to older areas or else run the risk of players simply not seeing any reason to spend much time in older zones. 
<br />
(continued....)</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
